{"@type":"Process","@id":"d2f534f3-3bd2-4b42-a9fa-bb963b461701","name":"Photovoltaic panel, single-Si; at plant","description":"This cradle-to-gate unit process dataset is for the production of 1 m2 of single crystalline silicon panel.\r\nThis unit process includes raw material acquisition; production; transport; production and use of fuels, and electricity; disposal of process waste; ancillary materials manufacturing; manufacture, and installation of capital equipment.","category":"31-33: Manufacturing/3359: Other Electrical Equipment and Component Manufacturing","version":"00.00.083","lastChange":"2025-07-18T15:31:46.446Z","processType":"UNIT_PROCESS","isInfrastructureProcess":false,"location":{"@type":"Location","@id":"0b3b97fa-6688-3c56-88ee-4ae80ec0c3c2","name":"United States"},"processDocumentation":{"validFrom":"2020-01-02","validUntil":"2020-11-30","timeDescription":"The period spans from the publication date of the latest study cited by Frischknecht et al. (2020) and the date of the publication of their report.","geographyDescription":"Frischknecht et al. (2020) is based on de Wild-Scholten (2014), and Woodhouse et al (2019). These reports do not specify the location from where their data was gathered.","technologyDescription":"According to Woodhouse et al. (2019) the assembly of single/multi-crystalline silicon panels “…involves electrically connecting cells into strings, arranging parallel cell strings into an array, electrically connecting the strings with metallic ribbons, mounting the array onto a layer of encapsulant on top of a sheet of glass or backsheet, and laminating another sheet of encapsulant and front glass onto the whole assembly. […] Front and back encapsulants […] melt […] when heated during the lamination process—thereby encasing the entire assembly between a sheet of glass on the front and either a backsheet or another sheet of glass on the back. The ribbons are fed through a hole in the back glass or backsheet and interwoven on the back of the module within a junction box, which contains diodes to reduce cell mismatch and serves as the point of contact between modules in an installed system. Finally, an extruded aluminum frame is typically put around the perimeter of the module”.","inventoryMethodDescription":"Attributional cradle-to-gate","modelingConstantsDescription":"Frischknecht et al. (2020) assumed heat losses were equal to the electricity used. \r\nFrischknecht et al. (2020) assumed emissions of water to air are assumed to be 10% of process water. They, however, refer to de Wild-Scholten (2014)’s inventory, which does not include water emissions.","completenessDescription":"Treatment of Missing Environmental Data\r\nFrischknecht et al. (2015, 2020), and de Wild-Scholten (2014) offer no information on cutoff criteria or flows that might have not been considered.\r\nTreatment of Missing Technosphere Data \r\nFrischknecht et al. (2015, 2020), and de Wild-Scholten (2014) offer no information on cutoff criteria or flows that might have not been considered.\r\nMass Balance\r\nThe mass balance for this process was not calculated. ","dataSelectionDescription":"This unit process was modeled based on Frischknecht et al. (2020) inventory for single crystalline silicon panels, available on Table 20 of said report. It is based de Wild-Scholten (2014), which is in turn partially based on de Wild-Scholten and Alsema (2007), and in Woodhouse et al. (2019).","dataTreatmentDescription":"The values in the LCI in Frischknecht et al. (2020) reflect the expert judgement of the authors and of the sources they cite, since none suggest a weighted average from different sources/reports.","samplingDescription":"System boundary conditions\r\nThe system boundary is cradle to gate and includes direct emissions, material and energy use, waste treatment, transport, and infrastructure. \r\nData collection\r\nThe data that made Frischknecht et al. (2020) LCI is based on previous reports. See “data selection” above and the original source for details.\r\nUncertainty\r\nFrischknecht et al. (2020) included a standard deviation for all flows, which is repeated here.","dataCollectionDescription":"Data to build this inventory ranges at least from the calendar year 2006 (some data nominally from de Wild-Scholten (2014) is from de Wild Scholten and Alsema (2007), whose data is from 2006 at the earliest) to 2018 (electricity use, based on Woodhouse et al., 2019) ","useAdvice":"None.","sources":[{"@type":"Source","@id":"2b683923-b652-45fe-90a2-ecacfe957cb6","name":"de Wild-Scholten and Alsema (2007) LCI PV","category":"NIST Sources"},{"@type":"Source","@id":"646de9dd-1f6f-4e71-8da6-2d5d4497eb82","name":"Frischknecht et al. (2020) LCI PV","category":"NIST Sources"},{"@type":"Source","@id":"9c9389d4-4ecf-4e10-bd29-8111257b5c93","name":"de Wild-Schloten (2014) LCI PV","category":"NIST Sources"},{"@type":"Source","@id":"992dbcb1-fd9f-4b19-bfb9-cc8db42f5e1f","name":"Frischknecht et al. (2015) LCI PV","category":"NIST Sources"},{"@type":"Source","@id":"46daf022-1c09-4b2d-890f-ec6314d1ffe3","name":"Woodhouse et al. (2019) Cost Si PV","category":"NIST Sources"}],"flowCompleteness":[{"aspect":"Freshwater ecotoxicity","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Renewable primary energy consumption","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Ozone depletion","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Noise","value":"All relevant flows quantified"},{"aspect":"Non-renewable primary energy depletion","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Acidification","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Human toxicity","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Species depletion","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Land use","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Non-renewable material resource depletion","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Eutrophication","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Particulate matter/respiratory inorganics","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Climate change","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Seawater eco-toxicity","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Summer smog","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Terrestric eco-toxicity","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Renewable material resource consumption","value":"No statement"},{"aspect":"Product model","value":"All relevant flows quantified"},{"aspect":"Radioactivity","value":"No statement"}],"reviews":[{"reviewType":"Not reviewed","scopes":[],"details":"It is likely the original report went through a review process, but because it is not explicitly mentioned, the data quality characteristic \"Process review\" was left as default (No documented review) and thus with a score of 5.","assessment":[{"aspect":"Technological representativeness","value":"Very good"},{"aspect":"Completeness","value":"Very good"},{"aspect":"Time representativeness","value":"Very good"},{"aspect":"Geographical representativeness","value":"Very good"}]}],"intendedApplication":"Situation C2 - Accounting, without system-external interactions - The intended application is a purely descriptive accounting / documentation of the analyzed system excluding interactions with other systems in the LCI model.\r\nThe target audience of this model are LCA practitioners, the silicon, solar and related industries and the general public. The inventory is considered largely complete, except for land transformation activities. For that reason, it is not recommended to use this dataset when evaluating land use impact categories. The results of the National Institute of Standards and Technology’s data gap analysis were analyzed using the ISO 21930-LCIA-US impact assessment methodology, as well as Cumulative Energy Demand and a subset of ReCiPe 2016 impact categories.\r\nThe original application of this dataset was the identification of data gaps in the Federal LCA Commons (FLCAC) (see \"Project\" above). However, the intended application is to provide a cradle-to-gate inventory (A1-A3, according to ISO 21930) using exclusively processes currently available in USLCI or generated as part of the project mentioned above, and elementary flows from the Federal Elementary Flow List (FEDEFL) to enable the use of a fuller range of LCIA impact categories than those reported in EPDs. For data quality purposes, the intended application is to provide a US average inventory for the year of publication of the original source. ","projectDescription":"This dataset was developed as part of the “Public Life Cycle Inventory Data Gap Analysis for Silicon-based Photovoltaic panels” National Institute of Standards and Technology’s Technical Note.","dataGenerator":{"@type":"Actor","@id":"dd386adb-2c05-4de6-8317-63943d599a8b","name":"Gonzalo Rodriguez-Garcia","category":"Persons"},"dataDocumentor":{"@type":"Actor","@id":"dd386adb-2c05-4de6-8317-63943d599a8b","name":"Gonzalo Rodriguez-Garcia","category":"Persons"},"creationDate":"2024-08-07T17:33:37.404Z","dataSetOwner":{"@type":"Actor","@id":"6c7dceb9-7426-4847-a719-db2eae447238","name":"National Institute of Standards and Technology","category":"Organisations"},"isCopyrightProtected":false,"restrictionsDescription":"This data/work was created by employees of the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), an agency of the Federal Government. Pursuant to title 17 United States Code Section 105, works of NIST employees are not subject to copyright protection in the United States.  This data/work may be subject to foreign copyright.\r\n\r\nThe data/work is provided by NIST as a public service and is expressly provided “AS IS.” NIST MAKES NO WARRANTY OF ANY KIND, EXPRESS, IMPLIED OR STATUTORY, INCLUDING, WITHOUT LIMITATION, THE IMPLIED WARRANTY OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, NON-INFRINGEMENT AND DATA ACCURACY. NIST does not warrant or make any representations regarding the use of the data or the results thereof, including but not limited to the correctness, accuracy, reliability or usefulness of the data. NIST SHALL NOT BE LIABLE AND YOU HEREBY RELEASE NIST FROM LIABILITY FOR ANY INDIRECT, CONSEQUENTIAL, SPECIAL